<section class="card leaderboardTableWrap">
  <h2>Search frost dates by city</h2>
  <p class="small">
    Search by city, province/state, or country. City names link to local planting-date pages with crop-specific timing. If you do not see your city listed here, use the <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a> to search by ZIP or postal code.
  </p>
  <label class="sr-only" for="frost-city-search">Search frost dates by city</label>
  <input
    id="frost-city-search"
    type="search"
    placeholder="Search city, province/state, or country..."
    autocomplete="off"
    style="width:100%;max-width:36rem;margin:0.75rem 0 1rem;padding:0.75rem 0.9rem;border:1px solid #d8e2d0;border-radius:999px;"
  />
  <p class="small" id="frost-city-search-count" aria-live="polite">
    Showing {{ frostDateReference.cityRecords.length }} cities.
  </p>
  <table id="frost-city-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>City</th>
        <th>Region</th>
        <th>Country</th>
        <th>Last spring frost</th>
        <th>First fall frost</th>
        <th>Frost-free days</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {% for row in frostDateReference.cityRecords %}
        <tr data-search="{{ row.cityName | lower }} {{ row.regionName | lower }} {{ row.regionAbbr | lower }} {{ row.countryLabel | lower }}">
          <td><strong><a href="{{ row.cityUrl }}">{{ row.cityName }}</a></strong></td>
          <td>{{ row.regionName }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.countryLabel }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.lastFrostLabel }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.firstFrostLabel }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.frostFreeDays }}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to use frost dates</h2>
  <p>
    Frost dates are planning anchors, not exact promises. The last spring frost helps estimate when frost-sensitive crops such as tomatoes, peppers, basil, cucumbers, squash, beans, corn, and melons can usually move outdoors.
    The first fall frost helps estimate whether a crop has enough time to size up, ripen, or finish before cold weather returns.
  </p>
  <ul class="tight">
    <li><strong>Last spring frost</strong> — the average date after which spring frost risk usually drops.</li>
    <li><strong>First fall frost</strong> — the average date when fall frost risk begins returning.</li>
    <li><strong>Frost-free days</strong> — the approximate number of days between those two dates.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A longer frost-free season gives warm-season crops more room to mature. A shorter season usually means earlier varieties, indoor starts, row cover, warm microclimates, or more conservative crop choices matter more.
    For a visual comparison of Canadian city seasons, see the <a href="/data/canada-garden-climate-atlas/">Canada Garden Climate Atlas</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card leaderboardCallout">
  <h2>What frost-free days do and do not tell you</h2>
  <p>
    Frost-free days are useful for comparing season length, but they do not tell the whole story. Two cities can have similar frost-free windows but very different summer heat.
    For heat-loving crops, compare this table with <a href="/data/growing-degree-days-by-city/">Growing Degree Days by City</a>.
    For a ranked view of the tightest seasons, see <a href="/data/rankings/cities-with-the-shortest-growing-seasons/">Cities With the Shortest Growing Seasons</a>.
  </p>
</section>


<section class="card">
  <h2>Common frost-date questions</h2>
  <details>
    <summary>Can I plant on the average last spring frost date?</summary>
    <p>Usually not for tender crops. The average last frost date is a planning reference, not a safety guarantee. Tomatoes, peppers, basil, cucumbers, squash, beans, corn, and melons should usually wait until the forecast is warm enough, nights are stable, and the soil has warmed.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Why might my garden frost later than the city average?</summary>
    <p>Low spots, exposed sites, rural edges, elevation, wind, shade, and cold-air drainage can all make a garden colder than the city average. Use the city date as a starting point, then adjust for your site.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What are frost-free days useful for?</summary>
    <p>Frost-free days help estimate the outdoor calendar window between spring and fall frost. They are useful for comparing season length, choosing faster varieties, and deciding whether crops need indoor starts or protection.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Are frost dates enough for warm-season crops?</summary>
    <p>No. Frost dates show the outdoor window, but they do not show how warm the season is. For tomatoes, peppers, corn, squash, cucumbers, and melons, compare frost dates with <a href="/data/growing-degree-days-by-city/">Growing Degree Days by City</a>.</p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What should I do if my city is not listed?</summary>
    <p>Use the <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a> to search by ZIP or postal code. Nearby cities can be useful for comparison, but elevation, distance from water, and local cold pockets can shift frost timing.</p>
  </details>
</section>

